&gt; 
&gt; I&#39;m implementing a sample TestListener. I&#39;ve encountered a number of 
&gt; unclear points I wanted to ask about. Here&#39;s the interface:
&gt; 
&gt; package org.junit.runner;
&gt; 
&gt; import java.lang.reflect.Method;
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; public interface TestListener {
&gt; 
&gt; 	void testRunStarted(int testCount);
&gt; 	
&gt; 	void testRunFinished(Runner runner); //TODO: Something 
&gt; is wrong here... 
&gt; Should take an event anyway
&gt; 	
&gt; 	void testStarted(Object test, String name);
&gt; 
&gt; 	void testFinished(Object test, String name);
&gt; 
&gt; 	void testFailure(Failure failure);
&gt; 
&gt; 	void testIgnored(Method method);
&gt; 
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; 1. What is the first argument passed to the testStarted and 
&gt; testFinished 
&gt; class? I assume this is the actual test object which in JUnit 4 can 
&gt; extend any class. Is it really helpful to pass this given 
&gt; that it&#39;s only 
&gt; an object of unspecified type and in practice may have any type?
&gt; 
&gt; 2. Why does testIgnored() get a Method when testFailure gets 
&gt; a Failure? 
&gt; Should there be an Ignored class? Or should testFailure take a method 
&gt; instead? These two feel out of sync.
&gt; 
&gt; 3. Does testFinished always bracket testStarted? i.e. does 
&gt; testFailure/testIgnored go in between started and finished or does it 
&gt; replace testFinished?

1. The first argument is the test object. I assume that it will be useful,
if only to print with toString(). I don&#39;t have any examples where it is
used, though, which makes me suspicious.

2. If a test is marked @Ignored, we don&#39;t create the test object at all.
However, we need a way to report the class and method that is being ignored.
Method is a handy collector of those two pieces of information.

3. testFinished() is always called.

We would like to move TestListener to an Event object style:
  interface TestListener {
    notify(TestEvent event);
  }

Or something like that. This makes it easier to extend TestListener in the
future (changes won&#39;t break existing code) at the expense of readability
(case logic in listener implemetations).

